  {
    "slug": "the-moral-storyscape-part-1",
    "title": "The Moral Storyscape: Part 1",
    "subtitle": "A Thematical Framework For Narrative Structure",
    "stream": "reports",
    "briefType": null,
    "date": "March 29, 2026",
    "substackUrl": "https://outpostmedia.substack.com/p/the-moral-storyscape-part-1",
    "thumbnail": "https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7ac0648e-af99-4b82-8b47-dc3f6e8bf8f3_1536x1024.png",
    "content": "\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7ac0648e-af99-4b82-8b47-dc3f6e8bf8f3_1536x1024.png\" alt=\"The Moral Storyscape Part 1\" class=\"article-hero-img\">\n\n      <p>Creative stories are restricted only to the limits of imagination itself, which, for all intents and purposes, is boundless. Nonetheless, all narratives have structure in some form or another. These various structures can be invaluable for writers in crafting a brilliant story. A solid structure provides the foundation for an engaging story. Sometimes, a framework to fall back on can be the difference between an author finishing a story and it being left on the cutting room floor.</p>\n\n      <p>A simple beginning, middle and end can be considered a narrative structure. The Hero's Journey is another example and is one of the most well-known types of narrative structures — but there are many, many more.</p>\n\n      <p>These frameworks help guide the author through creating the story. It helps the narrative appear complete and maintain internal logic. It also often provides much needed consistency across the story to ensure there's strong emotional resonance.</p>\n\n      <p>In this essay, I outline a novel and innovative narrative framework that arose during my own dabble in fictional writing known simply as — The Moral Storyscape.</p>\n\n      <p>The Moral Storyscape is a structure for the themes of a story and how characters can be vessels through which the themes are explored and demonstrated — which in turn provides a structure for how the narrative should unfold thematically.</p>\n\n      <p>Anyone who has ever tried writing a fictional story or narrative knows that it's much harder than it might initially seem.</p>\n\n      <p>One of the most difficult aspects of a story is nailing the themes of the story and how they're demonstrated throughout the narrative. It's often the execution of the themes that provides the difference between a critically acclaimed narrative and a flop.</p>\n\n      <h2>The Hero's Journey</h2>\n\n      <p>Before diving into the Moral Storyscape, I'll ease into the realm of narrative structures with the most common known example mentioned earlier — The Hero's Journey.</p>\n\n      <p>The Hero's Journey is a narrative structure that was first brought into the public consciousness by Joseph Campbell in a 1949 book titled \"The Hero with a Thousand Faces.\" In this book, Campbell explores his deep analysis of countless stories, legends and myths from a wide range of cultures and the patterns shared between them, producing a narrative framework that goes beyond the boundaries of genres and mediums.</p>\n\n      <p>Since the release of his book, Campbell's 'Hero's Journey' is evident in many of the most successful stories of the contemporary era.</p>\n\n      <p>The Hero's Journey is often segmented into defined plot points in a story. At a high level, it outlines the protagonist's transformation on their journey through adventure, challenge and personal evolution. The specific steps along the journey can be seen below.</p>\n\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F834de9d5-f324-49ab-898a-fbacd6383e37_912x779.png\" alt=\"The Hero's Journey diagram\" class=\"article-img\">\n\n      <p>Almost always beginning with 'The Ordinary World' &amp; 'The Call to Adventure' steps, where the hero is thrust from their old, established life into the unknown. Usually, it is followed by the meeting of a mentor before following a set of trials and tribulations, testing the character of the hero. Lastly, culminating in 'The Supreme Ordeal' and returning to their old life wiser and more powerful as a result of their journey.</p>\n\n      <p>Examples of the hero's journey are commonplace in popular culture stories. The Lord Of The Rings, Star Wars and The Lion King are a few amongst many well-known stories that follow the Hero's Journey.</p>\n\n      <p>In many ways, The Hero's Journey has become the default narrative structure of modern storytelling — a testament to its effectiveness and versatility. Yet, it holds no monopoly of narrative structures and exists as one amongst many options a writer has at their disposal.</p>\n\n      <p>In this essay I hope to add something to the arsenal of frameworks available, such that perhaps one day in the future, a writer may well equip themselves with The Moral Storyscape and produce an inspiring story for future generations, as the stories of my childhood did so for me.</p>\n\n      <h2>The Character Matrix</h2>\n\n      <p>The inspiration for the Moral Storyscape comes from the Character Matrix. A simpler type of narrative framework. In many ways, the Moral Storyscape acts as an extension of the Character Matrix, and thus it's important to understand what a Character Matrix is in order to understand the Moral Storyscape.</p>\n\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F16804f49-b568-4cd4-b47c-d88cfa02a12f_792x206.png\" alt=\"A blank Character Matrix\" class=\"article-img\">\n\n      <p>The simplest version of a Character Matrix is the 2 x 2 matrix (see the yellow cells above). The columns and rows represent two sides or opposing ends of a spectrum of two different topics. The sides and topics themselves can be just about anything depending on the story. The characters exhibit behaviours that relate to the one side of each topic. Each 'side' or spectrum end of each topic must be in opposition to the other. No characters may occupy two sides of the same theme.</p>\n\n      <p>The beauty of the Character Matrix is that it creates conflict and agreement between characters. Every character is in agreement with two characters and is also in conflict with two characters. Furthermore, every character has an 'arch enemy', if you will — someone who they share no agreement with. Finally, their position in the Character Matrix means that they occupy a unique set of beliefs and behaviours in the story (assuming one character per cell, which doesn't necessarily have to be the case). Again, we're looking at the simplest form here.</p>\n\n      <p>This may sound confusing without examples. Let's fill in the Character Matrix with some examples.</p>\n\n      <p>Before I do, I want to openly state that I have taken the below matrix from a YouTube video titled \"What Writers Should Learn From Batman Begins\" by \"JustWrite\". It's a great channel. Check it out if you're interested in this stuff. This is where I first discovered the concept of Character Matrix's and I'd like to give credit where it's due. I've changed things slightly here, but the original essence remains and demonstrates the point well.</p>\n\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb2828527-0c8b-45eb-9798-a951e9919c52_794x203.png\" alt=\"Batman Begins Character Matrix\" class=\"article-img\">\n\n      <p>For those who haven't seen Christopher Nolan's first instalment in the Batman trilogy (go watch it!) I'll briefly explain the characters here. Batman; goes without saying. Ra's al Ghul is Batman's ex-mentor and the leader of an international underground militant group called the 'League of Shadows' who believes in using violence and force to usher in a new and 'better' world. Scarecrow is a psychiatrist at Arkham Asylum who conducts sadistic experiments on inmates and criminals using his 'fear toxin' to further his research and personal goals. Finally, Carmine Falcone is the leader of Gotham City's largest crime family and exhibits all the classic mafia-leader traits, behaviours and ambitions.</p>\n\n      <p>Those who've seen the film can see this Character Matrix play out in the relationship and dialogue. For example, between Batman and Ra's al Ghul, it's the push and pull of their similarities (altruism) and differences (their method) that makes for the compelling dynamic between the duo. Similar can be said for the other relationships between the characters in the film.</p>\n\n      <p>So, I hope now I've made clear how a Character Matrix forms and some of the principles embedded within it are reflected in the narrative. This structure works great for a single narrative outlining two central topics — the opposing positions within them and where the characters fit within that.</p>\n\n      <p>What led me to develop The Moral Storyscape was that it didn't provide guidance on how the themes were explored over time. If the characters always occupied the same space or cell within the Character Matrix, would the story become stale? After all, don't characters go through 'character arcs' (another narrative structure), where they change and evolve to hold new ideas and values?</p>\n\n      <p>Again, things might become clearer with an example. Enter The Moral Storyscape.</p>\n\n      <h2>The Moral Storyscape</h2>\n\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F50bb8f4b-08bf-4d8d-8dc3-f9f1ff1f791a_816x601.png\" alt=\"A Blank Moral Storyscape\" class=\"article-img\">\n\n      <p>Let's begin with a breakdown of the Moral Storyscape template above, starting with the main difference from the Character Matrix. Here in the Moral Storyscape, the framework has developed from a matrix to essentially a graph. Rather than existing within discrete categories, the Moral Storyscape is continuous — some characters can be deep in their quadrant, others shallow. This allows more nuance to be embedded within the model and also allows for the structure to become kinetic as opposed to the static nature of the Character Matrix.</p>\n\n      <p>The other major change is the introduction of the 'Origin' and its implications. I've included the word 'Truth' next to the origin above, and I should explain what that means. Here the 'truth' is the moral truth. The phrase 'the moral of the story' is related to this. Each story has a moral truth that gets explored throughout the narrative; maybe it's as simple as 'honesty is the best policy'. A classic example of this is the fable 'The Boy Who Cried Wolf'. A character who exists in the origin would be someone who understands this moral truth and exhibits its behaviour. Someone on the far left, far right, very high or very low on the Moral Storyscape wouldn't understand this truth and wouldn't behave as if they did.</p>\n\n      <p>Another example of a character in the 'origin/truth' might be the tortoise from the fable 'The Tortoise and the Hare'. The moral truth is 'slow and steady wins the race'.</p>\n\n      <p>One heuristic to follow when using the Moral Storyscape is that characters who are close to the origin or 'the truth' fare better in the story than those away. When conveying the moral of the story, it's important that the moral characters are seen to be better off by adhering to the truth and those in the story who don't occupy this space receive the appropriate negative repercussions in the story. After all, part of showcasing 'the moral of the story' is that the moral/good guys 'win'.</p>\n\n      <p>The origin and its representation of this concept can assist a writer in deciding the fate of certain characters throughout the story.</p>\n\n      <p>Consider the example of 'The Boy Who Cried Wolf' mentioned above; for the X-axis, we could label it as the 'Honesty' axis. To attain what each 'side' of the axis should represent, start with the question, 'What two main aspects are required to make up the axis theme/moral?'. In this case for honesty multiple options are correct, but we could say for honesty that truthfulness and transparency are valid answers.</p>\n\n      <p>A question may arise now: if truthfulness and transparency are the two sides of the honesty axis where the origin is the truth, then does a character only on one side only adhere to one aspect of the theme?</p>\n\n      <p>This is a feature, not a bug, of the structure of The Moral Storyscape, as highlighting one aspect of the theme with the absence of another is how the theme is explored in depth. Let's look at truthfulness without transparency first.</p>\n\n      <p>Imagine a boss at a large company who is aware of an imminent large downsizing in the company — meaning a lot of people are about to lose their jobs. When they go to speak to their staff after hearing the news, they say 'to expect some changes' in the near future. While this is 100% factually correct and truthful, it's misleading and can result in a number of negative outcomes like anxiety and mistrust within the company down the line.</p>\n\n      <p>On the other hand, someone can be transparent and not truthful. Consider the archetypal sleazy second-hand car salesman, who gives numerous details on a car to a potential customer but exaggerates and speaks in half-truths or cherry-picks certain information about the state of the vehicle. It's clear how this could easily result in a bad outcome if the car is worse than conveyed.</p>\n\n      <p>A story that has two characters exemplifying either aspect of this trait is a way of exploring the theme of honesty.</p>\n\n      <p>The Moral Storyscape clearly isn't just one axis; however, it's two axes combined, creating the four quadrants that are reminiscent of the Character Matrix. It still has all of the benefits of a Character Matrix, such as clear character opposition and agreement, while adding the benefit of an 'origin' or central moral truth to assist in deciding the outcomes of characters. For the writer, by asking the question 'What are the two requirements to achieve themes X &amp; Y?' it also assists in understanding the themes of the story for themselves and clearly outlines the specific aspects to be explored within said themes.</p>\n\n      <p>I mentioned earlier that there is another main difference between the Character Matrix and Moral Storyscape and one is static and the other is kinetic. Before outlining exactly what this means, I think it's important to see a Moral Storyscape completely filled in and the steps taken to reach completion.</p>\n\n      <p><em>→ <a href=\"article.html?slug=the-moral-storyscape-part-2\" style=\"color:var(--gold)\">Continue to Part 2 →</a></em></p>\n    "
  },
  {
    "slug": "the-moral-storyscape-part-2",
    "title": "The Moral Storyscape: Part 2",
    "subtitle": "A Thematical Framework For Narrative Structure",
    "stream": "reports",
    "briefType": null,
    "date": "April 5, 2026",
    "substackUrl": "https://outpostmedia.substack.com/p/the-moral-storyscape-part-2",
    "thumbnail": "https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F9ae31a02-e5a3-4e53-b456-4576ae5bbdd2_1536x1024.png",
    "content": "\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F9ae31a02-e5a3-4e53-b456-4576ae5bbdd2_1536x1024.png\" alt=\"The Moral Storyscape Part 2\" class=\"article-hero-img\">\n\n      <p><em>In Part 1 I explored why narrative structures matter, beginning with familiar frameworks like the three-act structure, the Hero's Journey and a basic Character Matrix. Building on these foundations, I introduced my own addition to the narrative structure portfolio, the Moral Storyscape — a more dynamic, continuous model that uses axes, moral 'truth', and character movement to show how themes evolve across a story. In Part 2 I delve into more detail about how the Moral Storyscape can directly assist with narrative structure and storytelling.</em></p>\n\n      <p><em>→ <a href=\"article.html?slug=the-moral-storyscape-part-1\" style=\"color:var(--gold)\">Read Part 1 first</a></em></p>\n\n      <h2>A Complete Moral Storyscape</h2>\n\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F492c2295-dc32-43c3-a6f4-4f822b3d129d_814x596.png\" alt=\"My Personal Story's Moral Storyscape\" class=\"article-img\">\n\n      <p>Above, you can see the Moral Storyscape I developed for a personal fictional story. You can see the X-axis is 'Justice' and the Y-axis is 'Good' (as in good deeds or good acts). Like the honesty example from Part 1, the methodology for developing the two ends of each axis is to ask the question, \"What are the two main things that are required for the theme of my axis?\" So for example, to be 'good' requires having good intentions and producing good results. But all of this speaks nothing to the choice of the axis itself. While the Moral Storyscape doesn't have an explicit methodology for developing this, I think there's value in explaining how I got to mine.</p>\n\n      <h2>Developing the Choice of the Moral Storyscape Axes</h2>\n\n      <p>When trying to understand the themes of the story and developing this model, I was already in the process of writing, and I found it very difficult to specify exactly what the themes were. This was part of the problem that necessitated and inspired me to create the Moral Storyscape.</p>\n\n      <p>I thought it was best to think about what the classic themes are in fictional stories. Of course the obvious themes that came to mind were good and evil. These are the two archetypal themes of any narrative, and thus, they could act as the moral axis. So I decided to run with this, but I wanted to be more specific. I knew at this point that in the Moral Storyscape, the origin would represent the moral truth or the 'moral of the story'. So the natural next question is, what is the moral truth about 'good' and about 'evil'? Without getting too philosophical, I thought simply the moral truth is we want more 'good' and less 'evil' in the world. Again, however, this wasn't enough to define a theme or quadrant in the Moral Storyscape.</p>\n\n      <p>So I broke things down further, starting with evil. I thought to myself, 'How can evil be reduced?' or more accurately, 'What are the types of ways evil can be reduced?' Two answers came to mind. The obvious response is to purge it from the world wherever it can be found. The second thought I had was 'transform what is evil to that which is good'. Now I had two sides of the 'evil' axis I was looking for, but I needed a proper term to explain the two previous sentences. Hence, retributive &amp; restorative justice were born to act as a more grounded set of terms.</p>\n\n      <p>Turning to 'good', I asked myself the same question mentioned a couple of times before. 'What is required to achieve goodness?' Well, as inferred from the Moral Storyscape example above, the answer I came up with was good intentions and good results or outcomes.</p>\n\n      <p>Here, I had the four quadrants established, with both sides of both axes laid out. All I had to do was place each of the four main characters in their respective positions, completing the Moral Storyscape.</p>\n\n      <h2>The Moral Storyscape &amp; Narrative Structure</h2>\n\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F492c2295-dc32-43c3-a6f4-4f822b3d129d_814x596.png\" alt=\"My Personal Story's Moral Storyscape\" class=\"article-img\">\n\n      <p>Above, you have the same Moral Storyscape that I showed earlier for the story I'm writing. The Moral Storyscape I've envisioned here is to be where things sit at the end of the first book.</p>\n\n      <p>Therefore, while writing the first book, I can always refer back to this Moral Storyscape when I'm stuck on a thematic point or character choice. It can also provide significant guidance on what needs to be established in the first book.</p>\n\n      <p>For example, there should be a chapter or portion of a chapter dedicated to showcasing that Olivero believes in 'Restorative Justice' or Eliana values 'Good Intentions'. The absence of a trait is also important to convey — this could be done in the same chapter or at another time, bringing a minimum of 8 chapters/sections for each character and trait combination, if each is done separately and including absences. You can see how this can fill the story up quickly and provide ample guidance to a writer.</p>\n\n      <p>An important thing to note is most narrative chapters fall into one of two categories — action chapters and reaction chapters. Those are chapters where the plot is moving forward and change is occurring — action chapters — and chapters where the characters are reacting and discussing a recent action chapter.</p>\n\n      <p>It makes sense for certain values to align with chapter types. For example, a retributive justice chapter would be suited to an action chapter — if punishment is to be served, that sets the ground for an action-based chapter. Conversely, the 'good intentions' value is likely suited to a reaction chapter, where people are discussing and making decisions in which the value can be addressed. Although all values can go in either chapter, a well-thought-out story structure would take these points into account.</p>\n\n      <h2>The Evolving Moral Storyscape</h2>\n\n      <p>But we aren't finished here. I mentioned that one of the major differences between a Character Matrix and the Moral Storyscape was that the latter was kinetic, whereas the former was static. Let's finally discuss this.</p>\n\n      <p>I would guess that the majority of people reading this have heard of the term 'character arc'. It conveys the concept that the characters, through the events of the story, grow and change as a result of their experiences.</p>\n\n      <p>Well, if a character is to change over the course of a story, can we utilise a narrative structure to assist in the writing of this aspect of a story? The answer is, of course, yes!</p>\n\n      <p>If a character is to change over the course of the story, it's implied that their position in the Moral Storyscape would also change. There is a specific approach available using the Moral Storyscape that can cover all directions of all themes over three iterations. This will be more clear when seeing a second iteration.</p>\n\n      <p><strong>Second Iteration:</strong></p>\n\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F293164b6-2fed-49ca-8343-a80e0416c2af_814x572.png\" alt=\"My Personal Moral Storyscape — The Second Iteration\" class=\"article-img\">\n\n      <p>As you can see here, each character has moved from their original position in the Moral Storyscape, reflecting their evolution and their own character arcs.</p>\n\n      <p>The first important change here is that of Lucius and Olivero. Note that these two characters have only moved along one axis but have both arrived at the 'truth' for said axes. It's important that Lucius and Olivero do not meet or travel on the same axis, as it creates a conflict. If we have Olivero moving left towards the truth on the justice axis, while Lucius is moving right towards the truth on the justice axis, they in some ways cancel each other out.</p>\n\n      <p>Having the movements of the positively changed characters be on separate axes allows the themes to better play off one another and gives each character their own space to shine.</p>\n\n      <p>On the other hand, you have Eliana and Baylen moving further away from the origin at a 45-degree angle — implying they have moved along both axes in the wrong direction, i.e., further from the truth.</p>\n\n      <p>These two sets of changes would imply that the characters of Eliana and Baylen fare worse in the story, based upon the principle outlined earlier: that the further from the truth/origin a character is on the Moral Storyscape, the more ill their fate becomes, and vice versa for the fates of Olivero and Lucius.</p>\n\n      <p>However, sometimes the 'untruthful' characters need to be built up before they are brought down, and similarly, the 'truthful' characters need to go through adversity before their redemption. The Moral Storyscape here should act as a guide for the overall fate of the characters. Moment to moment throughout the story, things will not always be good or bad for either set of characters.</p>\n\n      <p>Of course, the Moral Storyscape doesn't have to play out exactly like this. Eliana and Baylen could move along only one axis themselves, or Lucius and Olivero could flip the axes they move across. This can be up to the writer's individual preference. The writer could even make the choice that only one character moves in the positive direction or a character joins another character in a new quadrant. All of these are viable options. The intention of the Moral Storyscape is to provide the framework that acts as a guide for conveying the themes of a story through the characters. The choice of how the Moral Storyscape looks and evolves throughout a narrative will look different for every story. Like any work of fiction, there are no right and wrong answers.</p>\n\n      <p><strong>Third Iteration:</strong></p>\n\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fddae9b34-ea4b-40da-b57b-6f6f341b7454_814x527.png\" alt=\"The Third Moral Storyscape Iteration\" class=\"article-img\">\n\n      <p>Above, you can see the final Moral Storyscape for my story. The change in position of the characters should appear intuitive, based upon the previous two iterations. Olivero and Lucius have now reached the origin or truth, while Baylen and Eliana have moved deeper into their respective corners and further from the truth. Again, Lucius and Olivero have moved in positive directions across different axes in order to ensure the themes don't appear in conflict to the audience.</p>\n\n      <p>Here is where the aspect of being closer or further from the truth is at its most important. By the end of the story it should be very clear that the characters at the origin (Olivero &amp; Lucius) are successful in the story, while the characters further from the truth (Baylen &amp; Eliana) are unsuccessful.</p>\n\n      <p>Now that all three iterations have been outlined, the value of the kinetic aspect of the Moral Storyscape can be understood in full. With the way this example of the Moral Storyscape has played out, literally every direction from every position has been covered, providing a complete exploration of the themes in the story.</p>\n\n      <p>That is, the story has explored healthy and unhealthy examples of each theme, and every character gets to occupy a unique exploration of each theme. See below for the complete breakdown, but for example Baylen is the only character who acts as the vehicle to explore the unhealthy aspects of valuing good results. While Lucius is the only character where the positive aspects of retributive justice are explored.</p>\n\n      <p><strong>Theme and Direction Breakdown:</strong></p>\n\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2bf91286-7612-402f-98d4-9d7906d186bb_814x177.png\" alt=\"Theme and Direction Breakdown\" class=\"article-img\">\n\n      <p>This point about the full exploration of the established themes in the story is one of the most beneficial aspects of the Moral Storyscape. As the characters undergo their separate arcs, there is a clear framework for how to explore the positive and negative aspects of each theme in full, leaving no stone unturned.</p>\n\n      <h2>Conclusion</h2>\n\n      <p>The best and most compelling narratives all use a structure in some form or another. Whether that's the classic three-act framework, Campbell's 'The Hero's Journey' or a Character Matrix, these are all bedrock examples of our favourite stories. It's my aspiration that the Moral Storyscape will add to the list of frameworks available for a writer to equip themselves with when crafting a brilliant story. It provides a writer with a strong thematical framework, utilising elements of a Character Matrix and builds upon it by the introduction of the 'origin' and its connection to the 'moral of the story', while also tying in the fate of the characters. Additionally, it accounts for the arcs of each character, represented in the freedom of their movement across the Moral Storyscape, resulting in a complete exploration of the themes while providing guidance for the writer at each stage of the story. The Moral Storyscape, I hope, is a tool to be considered for anyone's next major creative writing project.</p>\n\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb0ccdad6-cb80-457a-a59e-b000d3b8c1f3_1536x1024.png\" alt=\"The Moral Storyscape closing\" class=\"article-img\">\n    "
  },
  {
    "slug": "the-moral-storyscape-full",
    "title": "The Moral Storyscape: Full Essay",
    "subtitle": "A Thematical Framework For Narrative Structure — Parts 1 & 2",
    "stream": "reports",
    "briefType": null,
    "date": "April 6, 2026",
    "substackUrl": "https://outpostmedia.substack.com/p/the-moral-storyscape-part-1",
    "thumbnail": "https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7ac0648e-af99-4b82-8b47-dc3f6e8bf8f3_1536x1024.png",
    "content": "\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7ac0648e-af99-4b82-8b47-dc3f6e8bf8f3_1536x1024.png\" alt=\"The Moral Storyscape Part 1\" class=\"article-hero-img\">\n\n      <p>Creative stories are restricted only to the limits of imagination itself, which, for all intents and purposes, is boundless. Nonetheless, all narratives have structure in some form or another. These various structures can be invaluable for writers in crafting a brilliant story. A solid structure provides the foundation for an engaging story. Sometimes, a framework to fall back on can be the difference between an author finishing a story and it being left on the cutting room floor.</p>\n\n      <p>A simple beginning, middle and end can be considered a narrative structure. The Hero's Journey is another example and is one of the most well-known types of narrative structures — but there are many, many more.</p>\n\n      <p>These frameworks help guide the author through creating the story. It helps the narrative appear complete and maintain internal logic. It also often provides much needed consistency across the story to ensure there's strong emotional resonance.</p>\n\n      <p>In this essay, I outline a novel and innovative narrative framework that arose during my own dabble in fictional writing known simply as — The Moral Storyscape.</p>\n\n      <p>The Moral Storyscape is a structure for the themes of a story and how characters can be vessels through which the themes are explored and demonstrated — which in turn provides a structure for how the narrative should unfold thematically.</p>\n\n      <p>Anyone who has ever tried writing a fictional story or narrative knows that it's much harder than it might initially seem.</p>\n\n      <p>One of the most difficult aspects of a story is nailing the themes of the story and how they're demonstrated throughout the narrative. It's often the execution of the themes that provides the difference between a critically acclaimed narrative and a flop.</p>\n\n      <h2>The Hero's Journey</h2>\n\n      <p>Before diving into the Moral Storyscape, I'll ease into the realm of narrative structures with the most common known example mentioned earlier — The Hero's Journey.</p>\n\n      <p>The Hero's Journey is a narrative structure that was first brought into the public consciousness by Joseph Campbell in a 1949 book titled \"The Hero with a Thousand Faces.\" In this book, Campbell explores his deep analysis of countless stories, legends and myths from a wide range of cultures and the patterns shared between them, producing a narrative framework that goes beyond the boundaries of genres and mediums.</p>\n\n      <p>Since the release of his book, Campbell's 'Hero's Journey' is evident in many of the most successful stories of the contemporary era.</p>\n\n      <p>The Hero's Journey is often segmented into defined plot points in a story. At a high level, it outlines the protagonist's transformation on their journey through adventure, challenge and personal evolution. The specific steps along the journey can be seen below.</p>\n\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F834de9d5-f324-49ab-898a-fbacd6383e37_912x779.png\" alt=\"The Hero's Journey diagram\" class=\"article-img\">\n\n      <p>Almost always beginning with 'The Ordinary World' &amp; 'The Call to Adventure' steps, where the hero is thrust from their old, established life into the unknown. Usually, it is followed by the meeting of a mentor before following a set of trials and tribulations, testing the character of the hero. Lastly, culminating in 'The Supreme Ordeal' and returning to their old life wiser and more powerful as a result of their journey.</p>\n\n      <p>Examples of the hero's journey are commonplace in popular culture stories. The Lord Of The Rings, Star Wars and The Lion King are a few amongst many well-known stories that follow the Hero's Journey.</p>\n\n      <p>In many ways, The Hero's Journey has become the default narrative structure of modern storytelling — a testament to its effectiveness and versatility. Yet, it holds no monopoly of narrative structures and exists as one amongst many options a writer has at their disposal.</p>\n\n      <p>In this essay I hope to add something to the arsenal of frameworks available, such that perhaps one day in the future, a writer may well equip themselves with The Moral Storyscape and produce an inspiring story for future generations, as the stories of my childhood did so for me.</p>\n\n      <h2>The Character Matrix</h2>\n\n      <p>The inspiration for the Moral Storyscape comes from the Character Matrix. A simpler type of narrative framework. In many ways, the Moral Storyscape acts as an extension of the Character Matrix, and thus it's important to understand what a Character Matrix is in order to understand the Moral Storyscape.</p>\n\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F16804f49-b568-4cd4-b47c-d88cfa02a12f_792x206.png\" alt=\"A blank Character Matrix\" class=\"article-img\">\n\n      <p>The simplest version of a Character Matrix is the 2 x 2 matrix (see the yellow cells above). The columns and rows represent two sides or opposing ends of a spectrum of two different topics. The sides and topics themselves can be just about anything depending on the story. The characters exhibit behaviours that relate to the one side of each topic. Each 'side' or spectrum end of each topic must be in opposition to the other. No characters may occupy two sides of the same theme.</p>\n\n      <p>The beauty of the Character Matrix is that it creates conflict and agreement between characters. Every character is in agreement with two characters and is also in conflict with two characters. Furthermore, every character has an 'arch enemy', if you will — someone who they share no agreement with. Finally, their position in the Character Matrix means that they occupy a unique set of beliefs and behaviours in the story (assuming one character per cell, which doesn't necessarily have to be the case). Again, we're looking at the simplest form here.</p>\n\n      <p>This may sound confusing without examples. Let's fill in the Character Matrix with some examples.</p>\n\n      <p>Before I do, I want to openly state that I have taken the below matrix from a YouTube video titled \"What Writers Should Learn From Batman Begins\" by \"JustWrite\". It's a great channel. Check it out if you're interested in this stuff. This is where I first discovered the concept of Character Matrix's and I'd like to give credit where it's due. I've changed things slightly here, but the original essence remains and demonstrates the point well.</p>\n\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb2828527-0c8b-45eb-9798-a951e9919c52_794x203.png\" alt=\"Batman Begins Character Matrix\" class=\"article-img\">\n\n      <p>For those who haven't seen Christopher Nolan's first instalment in the Batman trilogy (go watch it!) I'll briefly explain the characters here. Batman; goes without saying. Ra's al Ghul is Batman's ex-mentor and the leader of an international underground militant group called the 'League of Shadows' who believes in using violence and force to usher in a new and 'better' world. Scarecrow is a psychiatrist at Arkham Asylum who conducts sadistic experiments on inmates and criminals using his 'fear toxin' to further his research and personal goals. Finally, Carmine Falcone is the leader of Gotham City's largest crime family and exhibits all the classic mafia-leader traits, behaviours and ambitions.</p>\n\n      <p>Those who've seen the film can see this Character Matrix play out in the relationship and dialogue. For example, between Batman and Ra's al Ghul, it's the push and pull of their similarities (altruism) and differences (their method) that makes for the compelling dynamic between the duo. Similar can be said for the other relationships between the characters in the film.</p>\n\n      <p>So, I hope now I've made clear how a Character Matrix forms and some of the principles embedded within it are reflected in the narrative. This structure works great for a single narrative outlining two central topics — the opposing positions within them and where the characters fit within that.</p>\n\n      <p>What led me to develop The Moral Storyscape was that it didn't provide guidance on how the themes were explored over time. If the characters always occupied the same space or cell within the Character Matrix, would the story become stale? After all, don't characters go through 'character arcs' (another narrative structure), where they change and evolve to hold new ideas and values?</p>\n\n      <p>Again, things might become clearer with an example. Enter The Moral Storyscape.</p>\n\n      <h2>The Moral Storyscape</h2>\n\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F50bb8f4b-08bf-4d8d-8dc3-f9f1ff1f791a_816x601.png\" alt=\"A Blank Moral Storyscape\" class=\"article-img\">\n\n      <p>Let's begin with a breakdown of the Moral Storyscape template above, starting with the main difference from the Character Matrix. Here in the Moral Storyscape, the framework has developed from a matrix to essentially a graph. Rather than existing within discrete categories, the Moral Storyscape is continuous — some characters can be deep in their quadrant, others shallow. This allows more nuance to be embedded within the model and also allows for the structure to become kinetic as opposed to the static nature of the Character Matrix.</p>\n\n      <p>The other major change is the introduction of the 'Origin' and its implications. I've included the word 'Truth' next to the origin above, and I should explain what that means. Here the 'truth' is the moral truth. The phrase 'the moral of the story' is related to this. Each story has a moral truth that gets explored throughout the narrative; maybe it's as simple as 'honesty is the best policy'. A classic example of this is the fable 'The Boy Who Cried Wolf'. A character who exists in the origin would be someone who understands this moral truth and exhibits its behaviour. Someone on the far left, far right, very high or very low on the Moral Storyscape wouldn't understand this truth and wouldn't behave as if they did.</p>\n\n      <p>Another example of a character in the 'origin/truth' might be the tortoise from the fable 'The Tortoise and the Hare'. The moral truth is 'slow and steady wins the race'.</p>\n\n      <p>One heuristic to follow when using the Moral Storyscape is that characters who are close to the origin or 'the truth' fare better in the story than those away. When conveying the moral of the story, it's important that the moral characters are seen to be better off by adhering to the truth and those in the story who don't occupy this space receive the appropriate negative repercussions in the story. After all, part of showcasing 'the moral of the story' is that the moral/good guys 'win'.</p>\n\n      <p>The origin and its representation of this concept can assist a writer in deciding the fate of certain characters throughout the story.</p>\n\n      <p>Consider the example of 'The Boy Who Cried Wolf' mentioned above; for the X-axis, we could label it as the 'Honesty' axis. To attain what each 'side' of the axis should represent, start with the question, 'What two main aspects are required to make up the axis theme/moral?'. In this case for honesty multiple options are correct, but we could say for honesty that truthfulness and transparency are valid answers.</p>\n\n      <p>A question may arise now: if truthfulness and transparency are the two sides of the honesty axis where the origin is the truth, then does a character only on one side only adhere to one aspect of the theme?</p>\n\n      <p>This is a feature, not a bug, of the structure of The Moral Storyscape, as highlighting one aspect of the theme with the absence of another is how the theme is explored in depth. Let's look at truthfulness without transparency first.</p>\n\n      <p>Imagine a boss at a large company who is aware of an imminent large downsizing in the company — meaning a lot of people are about to lose their jobs. When they go to speak to their staff after hearing the news, they say 'to expect some changes' in the near future. While this is 100% factually correct and truthful, it's misleading and can result in a number of negative outcomes like anxiety and mistrust within the company down the line.</p>\n\n      <p>On the other hand, someone can be transparent and not truthful. Consider the archetypal sleazy second-hand car salesman, who gives numerous details on a car to a potential customer but exaggerates and speaks in half-truths or cherry-picks certain information about the state of the vehicle. It's clear how this could easily result in a bad outcome if the car is worse than conveyed.</p>\n\n      <p>A story that has two characters exemplifying either aspect of this trait is a way of exploring the theme of honesty.</p>\n\n      <p>The Moral Storyscape clearly isn't just one axis; however, it's two axes combined, creating the four quadrants that are reminiscent of the Character Matrix. It still has all of the benefits of a Character Matrix, such as clear character opposition and agreement, while adding the benefit of an 'origin' or central moral truth to assist in deciding the outcomes of characters. For the writer, by asking the question 'What are the two requirements to achieve themes X &amp; Y?' it also assists in understanding the themes of the story for themselves and clearly outlines the specific aspects to be explored within said themes.</p>\n\n      <p>I mentioned earlier that there is another main difference between the Character Matrix and Moral Storyscape and one is static and the other is kinetic. Before outlining exactly what this means, I think it's important to see a Moral Storyscape completely filled in and the steps taken to reach completion.</p>\n\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F9ae31a02-e5a3-4e53-b456-4576ae5bbdd2_1536x1024.png\" alt=\"The Moral Storyscape Part 2\" class=\"article-img\">\n\n      <h2>A Complete Moral Storyscape</h2>\n\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F492c2295-dc32-43c3-a6f4-4f822b3d129d_814x596.png\" alt=\"My Personal Story's Moral Storyscape\" class=\"article-img\">\n\n      <p>Above, you can see the Moral Storyscape I developed for a personal fictional story. You can see the X-axis is 'Justice' and the Y-axis is 'Good' (as in good deeds or good acts). Like the honesty example from Part 1, the methodology for developing the two ends of each axis is to ask the question, \"What are the two main things that are required for the theme of my axis?\" So for example, to be 'good' requires having good intentions and producing good results. But all of this speaks nothing to the choice of the axis itself. While the Moral Storyscape doesn't have an explicit methodology for developing this, I think there's value in explaining how I got to mine.</p>\n\n      <h2>Developing the Choice of the Moral Storyscape Axes</h2>\n\n      <p>When trying to understand the themes of the story and developing this model, I was already in the process of writing, and I found it very difficult to specify exactly what the themes were. This was part of the problem that necessitated and inspired me to create the Moral Storyscape.</p>\n\n      <p>I thought it was best to think about what the classic themes are in fictional stories. Of course the obvious themes that came to mind were good and evil. These are the two archetypal themes of any narrative, and thus, they could act as the moral axis. So I decided to run with this, but I wanted to be more specific. I knew at this point that in the Moral Storyscape, the origin would represent the moral truth or the 'moral of the story'. So the natural next question is, what is the moral truth about 'good' and about 'evil'? Without getting too philosophical, I thought simply the moral truth is we want more 'good' and less 'evil' in the world. Again, however, this wasn't enough to define a theme or quadrant in the Moral Storyscape.</p>\n\n      <p>So I broke things down further, starting with evil. I thought to myself, 'How can evil be reduced?' or more accurately, 'What are the types of ways evil can be reduced?' Two answers came to mind. The obvious response is to purge it from the world wherever it can be found. The second thought I had was 'transform what is evil to that which is good'. Now I had two sides of the 'evil' axis I was looking for, but I needed a proper term to explain the two previous sentences. Hence, retributive &amp; restorative justice were born to act as a more grounded set of terms.</p>\n\n      <p>Turning to 'good', I asked myself the same question mentioned a couple of times before. 'What is required to achieve goodness?' Well, as inferred from the Moral Storyscape example above, the answer I came up with was good intentions and good results or outcomes.</p>\n\n      <p>Here, I had the four quadrants established, with both sides of both axes laid out. All I had to do was place each of the four main characters in their respective positions, completing the Moral Storyscape.</p>\n\n      <h2>The Moral Storyscape &amp; Narrative Structure</h2>\n\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F492c2295-dc32-43c3-a6f4-4f822b3d129d_814x596.png\" alt=\"My Personal Story's Moral Storyscape\" class=\"article-img\">\n\n      <p>Above, you have the same Moral Storyscape that I showed earlier for the story I'm writing. The Moral Storyscape I've envisioned here is to be where things sit at the end of the first book.</p>\n\n      <p>Therefore, while writing the first book, I can always refer back to this Moral Storyscape when I'm stuck on a thematic point or character choice. It can also provide significant guidance on what needs to be established in the first book.</p>\n\n      <p>For example, there should be a chapter or portion of a chapter dedicated to showcasing that Olivero believes in 'Restorative Justice' or Eliana values 'Good Intentions'. The absence of a trait is also important to convey — this could be done in the same chapter or at another time, bringing a minimum of 8 chapters/sections for each character and trait combination, if each is done separately and including absences. You can see how this can fill the story up quickly and provide ample guidance to a writer.</p>\n\n      <p>An important thing to note is most narrative chapters fall into one of two categories — action chapters and reaction chapters. Those are chapters where the plot is moving forward and change is occurring — action chapters — and chapters where the characters are reacting and discussing a recent action chapter.</p>\n\n      <p>It makes sense for certain values to align with chapter types. For example, a retributive justice chapter would be suited to an action chapter — if punishment is to be served, that sets the ground for an action-based chapter. Conversely, the 'good intentions' value is likely suited to a reaction chapter, where people are discussing and making decisions in which the value can be addressed. Although all values can go in either chapter, a well-thought-out story structure would take these points into account.</p>\n\n      <h2>The Evolving Moral Storyscape</h2>\n\n      <p>But we aren't finished here. I mentioned that one of the major differences between a Character Matrix and the Moral Storyscape was that the latter was kinetic, whereas the former was static. Let's finally discuss this.</p>\n\n      <p>I would guess that the majority of people reading this have heard of the term 'character arc'. It conveys the concept that the characters, through the events of the story, grow and change as a result of their experiences.</p>\n\n      <p>Well, if a character is to change over the course of a story, can we utilise a narrative structure to assist in the writing of this aspect of a story? The answer is, of course, yes!</p>\n\n      <p>If a character is to change over the course of the story, it's implied that their position in the Moral Storyscape would also change. There is a specific approach available using the Moral Storyscape that can cover all directions of all themes over three iterations. This will be more clear when seeing a second iteration.</p>\n\n      <p><strong>Second Iteration:</strong></p>\n\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F293164b6-2fed-49ca-8343-a80e0416c2af_814x572.png\" alt=\"My Personal Moral Storyscape — The Second Iteration\" class=\"article-img\">\n\n      <p>As you can see here, each character has moved from their original position in the Moral Storyscape, reflecting their evolution and their own character arcs.</p>\n\n      <p>The first important change here is that of Lucius and Olivero. Note that these two characters have only moved along one axis but have both arrived at the 'truth' for said axes. It's important that Lucius and Olivero do not meet or travel on the same axis, as it creates a conflict. If we have Olivero moving left towards the truth on the justice axis, while Lucius is moving right towards the truth on the justice axis, they in some ways cancel each other out.</p>\n\n      <p>Having the movements of the positively changed characters be on separate axes allows the themes to better play off one another and gives each character their own space to shine.</p>\n\n      <p>On the other hand, you have Eliana and Baylen moving further away from the origin at a 45-degree angle — implying they have moved along both axes in the wrong direction, i.e., further from the truth.</p>\n\n      <p>These two sets of changes would imply that the characters of Eliana and Baylen fare worse in the story, based upon the principle outlined earlier: that the further from the truth/origin a character is on the Moral Storyscape, the more ill their fate becomes, and vice versa for the fates of Olivero and Lucius.</p>\n\n      <p>However, sometimes the 'untruthful' characters need to be built up before they are brought down, and similarly, the 'truthful' characters need to go through adversity before their redemption. The Moral Storyscape here should act as a guide for the overall fate of the characters. Moment to moment throughout the story, things will not always be good or bad for either set of characters.</p>\n\n      <p>Of course, the Moral Storyscape doesn't have to play out exactly like this. Eliana and Baylen could move along only one axis themselves, or Lucius and Olivero could flip the axes they move across. This can be up to the writer's individual preference. The writer could even make the choice that only one character moves in the positive direction or a character joins another character in a new quadrant. All of these are viable options. The intention of the Moral Storyscape is to provide the framework that acts as a guide for conveying the themes of a story through the characters. The choice of how the Moral Storyscape looks and evolves throughout a narrative will look different for every story. Like any work of fiction, there are no right and wrong answers.</p>\n\n      <p><strong>Third Iteration:</strong></p>\n\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fddae9b34-ea4b-40da-b57b-6f6f341b7454_814x527.png\" alt=\"The Third Moral Storyscape Iteration\" class=\"article-img\">\n\n      <p>Above, you can see the final Moral Storyscape for my story. The change in position of the characters should appear intuitive, based upon the previous two iterations. Olivero and Lucius have now reached the origin or truth, while Baylen and Eliana have moved deeper into their respective corners and further from the truth. Again, Lucius and Olivero have moved in positive directions across different axes in order to ensure the themes don't appear in conflict to the audience.</p>\n\n      <p>Here is where the aspect of being closer or further from the truth is at its most important. By the end of the story it should be very clear that the characters at the origin (Olivero &amp; Lucius) are successful in the story, while the characters further from the truth (Baylen &amp; Eliana) are unsuccessful.</p>\n\n      <p>Now that all three iterations have been outlined, the value of the kinetic aspect of the Moral Storyscape can be understood in full. With the way this example of the Moral Storyscape has played out, literally every direction from every position has been covered, providing a complete exploration of the themes in the story.</p>\n\n      <p>That is, the story has explored healthy and unhealthy examples of each theme, and every character gets to occupy a unique exploration of each theme. See below for the complete breakdown, but for example Baylen is the only character who acts as the vehicle to explore the unhealthy aspects of valuing good results. While Lucius is the only character where the positive aspects of retributive justice are explored.</p>\n\n      <p><strong>Theme and Direction Breakdown:</strong></p>\n\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2bf91286-7612-402f-98d4-9d7906d186bb_814x177.png\" alt=\"Theme and Direction Breakdown\" class=\"article-img\">\n\n      <p>This point about the full exploration of the established themes in the story is one of the most beneficial aspects of the Moral Storyscape. As the characters undergo their separate arcs, there is a clear framework for how to explore the positive and negative aspects of each theme in full, leaving no stone unturned.</p>\n\n      <h2>Conclusion</h2>\n\n      <p>The best and most compelling narratives all use a structure in some form or another. Whether that's the classic three-act framework, Campbell's 'The Hero's Journey' or a Character Matrix, these are all bedrock examples of our favourite stories. It's my aspiration that the Moral Storyscape will add to the list of frameworks available for a writer to equip themselves with when crafting a brilliant story. It provides a writer with a strong thematical framework, utilising elements of a Character Matrix and builds upon it by the introduction of the 'origin' and its connection to the 'moral of the story', while also tying in the fate of the characters. Additionally, it accounts for the arcs of each character, represented in the freedom of their movement across the Moral Storyscape, resulting in a complete exploration of the themes while providing guidance for the writer at each stage of the story. The Moral Storyscape, I hope, is a tool to be considered for anyone's next major creative writing project.</p>\n\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb0ccdad6-cb80-457a-a59e-b000d3b8c1f3_1536x1024.png\" alt=\"The Moral Storyscape closing\" class=\"article-img\">\n    "
  },
  {
    "slug": "new-atheism-and-the-internet-age",
    "title": "New Atheism & The Internet Age: A Rise & Fall",
    "subtitle": "An overview of the changes to religious views in society since the beginning of digitalisation",
    "stream": [
      "atheism",
      "reports"
    ],
    "briefType": null,
    "date": "March 15, 2026",
    "substackUrl": "https://outpostmedia.substack.com/p/new-atheism-and-the-internet-age",
    "thumbnail": "https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff132b85f-0866-4bee-8897-135a5ab3a35b_1280x720.jpeg",
    "content": "\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff132b85f-0866-4bee-8897-135a5ab3a35b_1280x720.jpeg\" alt=\"New Atheism and the Internet Age\" class=\"article-hero-img\">\n\n      <p>One of the defining features of the Internet Age is the sheer volume of information we consume daily. You may have heard the idea popularised by Richard Wurman that a single copy of <em>The New York Times</em> contains more information than a normal person would consume in one lifetime living in 17th-century England.</p>\n\n      <p>We have all felt the whiplash and subsequent amnesia from a news cycle that has the vicious speed of a dodgy rollercoaster.</p>\n\n      <p>In saying that, I do want to try to bring you back almost twenty years ago now, to 2007.</p>\n\n      <p>A lifetime ago for some and just the other day for others, let me remind you of what 2007 looked like: Apple released the original version of the iPhone, the first dominoes of the subprime mortgage crisis fell, and the final Harry Potter book was unveiled.</p>\n\n      <p>The mid-to-late 2000s were a unique moment in cultural and technological history. The internet was still in its adolescence, and platforms like YouTube and social media were in their formative years.</p>\n\n      <p>These digital tools created an unprecedented opportunity for voices to spread, unfiltered and unmediated, across the globe.</p>\n\n      <p>Among these voices were the Four Horsemen of the New Atheist movement — journalist Christopher Hitchens, evolutionary biologist Richard Dawkins, philosopher and neuroscientist Sam Harris, and philosopher Daniel Dennett — who challenged the dominance of religion in public life and ignited a cultural revolution.</p>\n\n      <p>However, in the years since, the movement they sparked has faded, and religion is making a comeback.</p>\n\n      <h2>The Rise of the Four Horsemen &amp; New Atheism</h2>\n\n      <p>'The Four Horsemen' is a somewhat sarcastic moniker, given the group was made up of four of the most well-known atheists on the planet. It plays on the biblical Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse from the Book of Revelation; the group was also commonly referred to as 'The New Atheists'.</p>\n\n      <p>Harris, motivated by the events of September 11, 2001, could be argued to have started the 'new atheist movement' through his 2004 book, <em>The End of Faith</em>, which he followed up two years later with <em>Letters to a Christian Nation</em>. Also, in 2006 Dawkins released <em>The God Delusion</em> and Dennett <em>Breaking the Spell</em>. The following year, 2007, Hitchens' <em>God is Not Great</em> completed the unofficial set.</p>\n\n      <p>While the Four Horsemen dominated the movement, an honourable mention should also go out to Somali-born Dutch-American writer and former politician Ayaan Hirsi-Ali, who at the time was often dubbed the 'fifth horseman' or 'one horsewoman' by Dawkins (Hirsi-Ali, as of 2023, has converted to Christianity, a telling anecdote for this piece).</p>\n\n      <p>The year 2007 saw the group sit down for a round table discussion (<a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9DKhc1pcDFM\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Part 1 &amp; Part 2</a>) on YouTube titled \"The Four Horsemen\". In 2019 the discussion was immortalised in a book titled <em>The Four Horsemen: The Conversation That Sparked an Atheist Revolution</em> with opening essays from all surviving members (Hitchens had passed away in 2011), followed by a transcript of the discussion referenced.</p>\n\n      <p>Dawkins later reflected on the term \"New Atheists\", noting, <em>\"I don't object to the horseman label, by the way. I'm less keen on 'new atheists': it isn't clear to me how we differ from old atheists.\"</em></p>\n\n      <p>The Four Horsemen were undeniably a product of their time. In the post-9/11 world, their critiques of religion – particularly its links to violence and oppression – struck a resonant chord with audiences.</p>\n\n      <p>The new atheist movement was far-reaching and for those who had conservative religious upbringings, it was often the first and almost certainly the most coherent and public counter-narrative to their faith they had seen or heard. Even for atheists who already agreed with their positions, the Horsemen provided a sense of solidarity and equipped their followers with compelling arguments.</p>\n\n      <p>Hitchens, in particular, became known for his sharp wit, rhetorical brilliance and unfailing resolve, even during his final years while suffering from (and ultimately succumbing to) oesophageal cancer.</p>\n\n      <p>The New Atheist rise coincided with (or perhaps brought on) a cultural shift. The graph below from an Atlantic article shows a large uptick in those 'unaffiliated' with religion in 2004 right when the first book in the unofficial New Atheist set (Harris' <em>The End Of Faith</em>) was released.</p>\n\n      <p>Of course, this is a massively multivariable phenomenon, but also, I believe, not a coincidence. Whether the Four Horsemen were a symptom or the cause of the changing environment is debatable; what isn't is that they were deeply intertwined with it.</p>\n\n      <h2>The Decline of the New Atheist Movement</h2>\n\n      <p>While the Four Horsemen sparked a cultural revolution, the movement's momentum began to wane as the cultural landscape shifted towards the late 2010s. The factors that once amplified their message – such as the openness of the early internet – began to change, and new priorities emerged.</p>\n\n      <p>The death of Christopher Hitchens in 2011 marked the loss of its most charismatic and combative voice; this, along with the eroding effects of time, saw the new atheist movement whittle away almost entirely.</p>\n\n      <p>Since the rise of the New Atheists, the culture and the internet itself have changed. Platforms like YouTube and social media have become increasingly fragmented, with algorithms creating echo chambers that limit the reach of ideas across ideological boundaries. Where the Four Horsemen once thrived in a relatively open digital landscape, today's internet is oversaturated and polarised, making it harder for movements like New Atheism to achieve the same impact.</p>\n\n      <p>Additionally, as social justice movements and identity politics started to take centre stage, public discourse shifted away from religion as the primary battleground. Issues like race, gender, and systemic inequality became dominant cultural conversations, leaving little room for the confrontational tone of New Atheism.</p>\n\n      <p>Nature cannot stand a vacuum, and like many things in life and culture, it appears as if the pendulum has swung the other way.</p>\n\n      <p>Many well-known online personas have either famously converted to religion or were already religious. Consider the below figures, and know many more could've been added.</p>\n\n      <ul style=\"color:#d8d4ce; margin: 1em 0 1.5em 1.5em; line-height: 2;\">\n        <li>Jordan Peterson – 9M YouTube subscribers – Christianity</li>\n        <li>Andrew Tate – 10.7M X followers – Islam</li>\n        <li>Ayaan Hirsi Ali (mentioned above) – 560k X followers – Christianity</li>\n        <li>Ben Shapiro – 7M YouTube &amp; X followers – Judaism</li>\n        <li>Russell Brand – 11M X followers – Christianity</li>\n        <li>Candace Owens – 7M X followers – Christianity</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <p>Even Joe Rogan, the host of The Joe Rogan Experience and one of the most influential figures in modern digital media, has <a href=\"https://churchleaders.com/news/512905-joe-rogan-discusses-attending-church.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">mentioned</a> he has been attending church lately.</p>\n\n      <p>The influence of these figures reflects a growing appetite for meaning and structure in a fragmented world. In many ways, despite their obvious differences, those mentioned above occupy the cultural space once held by the Four Horsemen.</p>\n\n      <p>Even though these religious figures are predominantly considered 'right-wing', and thus a slightly biassed set, I believe their influence is emblematic of a broader trend: religion is making a comeback.</p>\n\n      <p>The numbers speak for themselves. Tens of millions of people are followers of these figures, which doesn't include all those consuming the content who aren't direct subscribers. The combined reach of only those mentioned above is enormous, and to deny the impact of their conversions or religious beliefs – on individuals and the culture more broadly – is shortsighted. In the same way that underestimating the impact of the Four Horsemen during their time is equally ignorant.</p>\n\n      <h2>The Numbers</h2>\n\n      <p>There are numbers that back up this declining 'unaffiliated with religion' trend. Contrasting the rise in atheism mentioned above during the mid-2000s I'd like to reference this <a href=\"https://www.pewresearch.org/religion/2024/01/24/religious-nones-in-america-who-they-are-and-what-they-believe/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Pew Research Center article</a> on religious 'nones' from January 2024. Specifically, the graph featured below, showcasing from 2022 to 2023 a drop from ~31% 'nones' in the US to 28%, reversing over a decade of growth.</p>\n\n      <p>Another Pew Research Center article projects that there will be more unaffiliated religious people in the decades to come, but as a percentage of the global population, it will fall. Birth rates of religious versus non-religious people are playing a massive role here along with the shifting cultural dynamic.</p>\n\n      <p>To add even more evidence for the resurgence of religiosity, let me add a few more statistics.</p>\n\n      <p>This <a href=\"https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/industry-news/religion/article/99415-bible-sales-hit-records-in-us-and-uk.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Publishers Weekly article</a> states that in 2025 \"Bible sales — which have been on the rise since 2021 — hit record highs in the U.S. and the UK, according to statistics drawn from Circana BookScan.\" The article continues that in the US Bible sales were \"up 12% compared to 2024 and double the number of units sold in 2019\" and in the UK \"Bible sales last year were 134% higher than in 2008.\"</p>\n\n      <p>The <a href=\"https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2026/jan/14/christian-rock-latin-lead-music-streaming-growth-us-5-trillion-2025/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Washington Times</a> also reported that \"Christian/gospel music has continued to grow stateside: up 18.5% in on-demand audio volume change compared to 2024\".</p>\n\n      <p>Outside of the statistics, it feels as if culturally, that religion is playing a bigger role in our societies. Whether that's the influence of the Bondi massacre recently here in Australia, Rupert Lowe's formation of the Restore Britain party in the UK or just the recent Middle Eastern wars, I think it's safe to say that religion has once again become a major element of the zeitgeist and New Atheism merely a whisper of a time gone by, lost to the winds of history.</p>\n\n      <h2>Conclusion</h2>\n\n      <p>The decline of the New Atheism movement has left a void in public discourse. With only half of the Four Horsemen still alive, Dawkins at 84 years old and Sam Harris largely stepping away from the subject, their time has clearly passed. The changing landscape is undoubtedly now in the hands of theists.</p>\n\n      <p>However, it is my belief that it is important to have checks and balances on religions' impact on society. That pushing back on its tribalistic and extremist tendencies is important to ensure the future vitality of our society.</p>\n\n      <p>The pendulum is indeed swinging in the direction of religiosity, however, it won't stay that way, as is the physical nature of such a system.</p>\n\n      <p>Since the beginning of the Internet Age, New Atheism was born, made a magnificent rise, experienced a dramatic fall, and now it very well may never return. However, the phoenix that grows out of the ashes of its demise will be a fascinating and important creature to watch, catching flight in the background of our cultural moment.</p>\n\n      <p>As religion takes centre stage once again, what I hope to explore in the coming editions of Honest Atheism is what form this new, New Atheism may take as the successor of one of the biggest cultural events of the Internet Age.</p>\n\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa395d2a2-ab0f-4759-9254-3b916f0a79f4_1024x969.jpeg\" alt=\"New Atheism and the Internet Age closing\" class=\"article-img\">\n    "
  }
